WEBVTT

00:00:01.280 --> 00:00:07.280
<v Speaker 1>The word for boring or bought is aborido

00:00:08.120 --> 00:00:09.320
<v Speaker 1>Aburido.

00:00:09.320 --> 00:00:10.520
<v Speaker 2>Aburido.

00:00:10.520 --> 00:00:15.320
<v Speaker 1>A B U R R I D O Aburido.

00:00:15.320 --> 00:00:16.520
<v Speaker 2>Aburido.

00:00:16.520 --> 00:00:18.840
<v Speaker 1>Now this is boring or bored

00:00:19.340 --> 00:00:23.500
<v Speaker 1>One of these words in English is a characteristic and the other one is a state.

00:00:23.500 --> 00:00:25.020
<v Speaker 1>Which is which?

00:00:25.020 --> 00:00:26.220
<v Speaker 1>Boring.

00:00:26.220 --> 00:00:30.220
<v Speaker 1>If I say you are boring, is it a state or a characteristic

00:00:30.740 --> 00:00:31.860
<v Speaker 1>Characteristic.

00:00:31.860 --> 00:00:35.700
<v Speaker 1>And if I say you are bored, is it a state or a characteristic?

00:00:36.020 --> 00:00:36.740
<v Speaker 1>A state.

00:00:36.740 --> 00:00:37.300
<v Speaker 1>A state.

00:00:37.300 --> 00:00:39.860
<v Speaker 1>So in English we have two different words.

00:00:39.520 --> 00:00:41.600
<v Speaker 1>To express this difference.

00:00:41.600 --> 00:00:47.120
<v Speaker 1>Whereas in Spanish you will just decide whether you're going to use ser or estar.

00:00:47.120 --> 00:00:49.440
<v Speaker 1>So you'll have to think about it.

00:00:49.440 --> 00:00:52.240
<v Speaker 1>How will you say it is boring?

00:00:53.160 --> 00:00:54.840
<v Speaker 2>Es aborido.

00:00:54.840 --> 00:00:56.120
<v Speaker 1>Es aburrido.

00:00:56.120 --> 00:00:56.760
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:00:57.080 --> 00:00:58.760
<v Speaker 1>He is bored.

00:00:58.760 --> 00:01:01.240
<v Speaker 1>Is it a characteristic or a state?

00:01:02.760 --> 00:01:03.560
<v Speaker 2>State.

00:01:03.560 --> 00:01:04.120
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:01:04.120 --> 00:01:06.920
<v Speaker 1>So he is bored.

00:01:07.220 --> 00:01:09.140
<v Speaker 2>Esta aburido.

00:01:09.140 --> 00:01:10.580
<v Speaker 1>Esta aburrido.

00:01:10.580 --> 00:01:13.220
<v Speaker 1>But he is boring.

00:01:13.220 --> 00:01:14.420
<v Speaker 2>Es aburido.

00:01:14.420 --> 00:01:14.659
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:01:14.659 --> 00:01:16.420
<v Speaker 1>And she is boring?

00:01:17.579 --> 00:01:18.780
<v Speaker 2>Es aburrido.

00:01:18.780 --> 00:01:21.740
<v Speaker 2>Oh sorry, ella es aburrido.

00:01:22.460 --> 00:01:24.539
<v Speaker 1>Spanish is more subtle than that.

00:01:25.020 --> 00:01:26.140
<v Speaker 1>Es aburrida.

00:01:28.140 --> 00:01:30.220
<v Speaker 1>They are boring.

00:01:31.520 --> 00:01:33.520
<v Speaker 1>Son aburridos.

00:01:33.520 --> 00:01:35.680
<v Speaker 1>Son aburridos.

00:01:35.680 --> 00:01:38.160
<v Speaker 1>They abode.

00:01:38.320 --> 00:01:40.000
<v Speaker 2>Stan aburidos.

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:40.960
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:01:40.560 --> 00:01:42.080
<v Speaker 1>Están aburridos.

00:01:42.080 --> 00:01:49.200
<v Speaker 1>So with some adjectives we get a different meaning depending on whether we use ser or estar.

00:01:49.200 --> 00:01:52.880
<v Speaker 1>The word for from in Spanish is de.

00:01:55.020 --> 00:02:03.500
<v Speaker 1>De we get this forming part of many Latin English words, for example deliver.

00:02:03.500 --> 00:02:07.740
<v Speaker 1>The de of deliver is actually from leva is

00:02:08.580 --> 00:02:17.140
<v Speaker 1>to do with freedom like liberation liberation how would you say to liberate liberar good

00:02:17.599 --> 00:02:20.400
<v Speaker 1>Libre is free in Spanish.

00:02:20.400 --> 00:02:26.959
<v Speaker 1>So again we see this gray area between V and B, between English and Spanish, between

00:02:27.040 --> 00:02:35.120
<v Speaker 1>Libre and liver in the liver, just as we did between savi and saber, for example.

00:02:35.120 --> 00:02:37.200
<v Speaker 1>So the liver is like

00:02:37.620 --> 00:02:46.500
<v Speaker 1>from or of uh freeing which has much more sense if you look at the original meanings of deliver like to deliver a baby

00:02:46.720 --> 00:02:52.159
<v Speaker 1>Deliver me from evil rather than to deliver a package, which is a much more modern meaning.

00:02:52.159 --> 00:02:54.000
<v Speaker 1>You can see much more the

00:02:54.420 --> 00:02:58.100
<v Speaker 1>the ideology in the vocabulary with the other uses.

00:02:58.100 --> 00:03:01.940
<v Speaker 1>Another interesting word that we can see this the in in English

00:03:02.020 --> 00:03:04.020
<v Speaker 1>is a decipher for example.

00:03:04.020 --> 00:03:08.420
<v Speaker 1>Decipher is actually a combination of Arabic and Latin.

00:03:08.420 --> 00:03:11.060
<v Speaker 1>You have their meaning of or from.

00:03:10.700 --> 00:03:14.300
<v Speaker 1>And cipher from sufr, which means zero in Arabic.

00:03:14.300 --> 00:03:19.260
<v Speaker 1>So to decipher is to to go from zero or something like this.

00:03:19.040 --> 00:03:22.960
<v Speaker 1>So anyway, we have the for from or of.

00:03:22.960 --> 00:03:30.560
<v Speaker 1>Now if I want to ask where is he from, is it a characteristic or a state where you are from?

00:03:31.320 --> 00:03:32.520
<v Speaker 1>A characteristic.

00:03:32.520 --> 00:03:33.800
<v Speaker 1>Yes, it's not where you are.

00:03:33.800 --> 00:03:34.760
<v Speaker 1>It's where you are from.

00:03:34.760 --> 00:03:36.600
<v Speaker 1>This is characteristic of you.

00:03:36.600 --> 00:03:38.920
<v Speaker 1>So in Spanish we're gonna say from where

00:03:39.720 --> 00:03:40.439
<v Speaker 1>Are you?

00:03:40.439 --> 00:03:41.799
<v Speaker 1>From where is he?

00:03:41.799 --> 00:03:42.920
<v Speaker 1>From where is she?

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:44.360
<v Speaker 1>This is the word order.

00:03:44.360 --> 00:03:46.760
<v Speaker 1>So from where is what?

00:03:46.760 --> 00:03:47.720
<v Speaker 2>De dónde?

00:03:47.720 --> 00:03:48.760
<v Speaker 1>De dónde?

00:03:48.760 --> 00:03:49.959
<v Speaker 1>From where is he?

00:03:49.959 --> 00:03:50.840
<v Speaker 1>From where are you?

00:03:50.840 --> 00:03:51.640
<v Speaker 1>Fumel?

00:03:51.640 --> 00:03:52.519
<v Speaker 1>Etc.

00:03:53.180 --> 00:03:54.620
<v Speaker 2>De dónde s?

00:03:54.860 --> 00:03:56.140
<v Speaker 1>De dónde es?

00:03:56.140 --> 00:03:59.420
<v Speaker 1>And u informal, you remember how is UR, u informal?

00:03:59.420 --> 00:04:01.019
<v Speaker 1>It's kind of similar to S

00:04:02.220 --> 00:04:03.580
<v Speaker 2>De dónde eres?

00:04:03.580 --> 00:04:04.940
<v Speaker 1>De dónde eres?

00:04:04.940 --> 00:04:10.940
<v Speaker 1>So this sentence actually will help you remember this kind of irregular form, eres, because you will hear it all the time.

00:04:11.100 --> 00:04:12.300
<v Speaker 1>De dónde eres?

00:04:12.300 --> 00:04:13.580
<v Speaker 1>From where are you?

00:04:13.580 --> 00:04:15.260
<v Speaker 1>Where are you from?

00:04:15.580 --> 00:04:18.380
<v Speaker 1>How would you say where are they from?

00:04:19.740 --> 00:04:20.780
<v Speaker 2>They don't design.

00:04:21.980 --> 00:04:27.340
<v Speaker 1>But if you want to ask where are they, the location, where are they, how would you ask?

00:04:27.920 --> 00:04:29.200
<v Speaker 1>Donde stan.

00:04:29.200 --> 00:04:29.840
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:04:29.840 --> 00:04:33.360
<v Speaker 1>Donde stan because now we refer to a state.

00:04:33.360 --> 00:04:34.640
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:04:34.640 --> 00:04:42.000
<v Speaker 1>So we have this adjective as well, libre, like in deliver, liberation, libre, which means free.

00:04:41.860 --> 00:04:47.300
<v Speaker 1>Again, we might mean a state or we might mean characteristic.

00:04:47.300 --> 00:04:51.940
<v Speaker 1>Now sometimes to show the difference we might not just

00:04:52.560 --> 00:04:57.120
<v Speaker 1>Use ser and star, we might actually also change the way we say it.

00:04:57.120 --> 00:04:59.760
<v Speaker 1>So for example, if you want to say I am free

00:05:00.039 --> 00:05:03.479
