<v Speaker 1>What's a person?

00:05:46.460 --> 00:05:47.500
<v Speaker 2>Una persona.

00:05:47.500 --> 00:05:47.820
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:05:47.820 --> 00:05:49.820
<v Speaker 1>I am a free person.

00:05:50.300 --> 00:05:52.620
<v Speaker 2>Soy una persona libre.

00:05:52.620 --> 00:05:53.100
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:05:53.100 --> 00:05:55.340
<v Speaker 1>Soy una persona libre.

00:05:55.500 --> 00:05:59.260
<v Speaker 1>Persona is feminine, not because of you, because the word is feminine.

00:05:59.260 --> 00:06:03.900
<v Speaker 1>So I, as a male, would also say, soy una persona libre.

00:06:03.900 --> 00:06:07.980
<v Speaker 1>So it's the noun in itself, persona, that is feminine.

00:06:07.740 --> 00:06:13.980
<v Speaker 1>So in this case with libre, there's no problem to move between ser and the star.

00:06:13.980 --> 00:06:18.700
<v Speaker 1>You can use libre with ser or with a star to give slightly different meanings

00:06:18.760 --> 00:06:24.360
<v Speaker 1>So some adjectives you will be able to move between ser and star and others you won't.

00:06:24.360 --> 00:06:28.120
<v Speaker 1>If you want to get around that uncertainty instead of uh

00:06:28.620 --> 00:06:33.979
<v Speaker 1>trying out soy libre, you could just say soy una persona libre.

00:06:33.979 --> 00:06:43.180
<v Speaker 1>And then because persona is going with soy, because what you are saying in fact is I am a person, soy una persona, then you know you're safe.

00:06:43.380 --> 00:06:50.340
<v Speaker 1>Also, different Spanish dialects can have different ideas about what should go with ser and what should go with a estar.

00:06:50.340 --> 00:06:54.259
